Black's play and equalise} (13... bxc6 14. dxe5 Nd7 (14... Ne4 $5 15. Nxe4 dxe4
16. Qd6 Bf5 $11) 15. f4 Rb8 16. b3 $14 {1/2 (39) Grischuk,A (2777)-Wei,Y (2732)
Chess.com INT 2020}) 14. Kxh2 Rxe1 15. Qxe1 Qc7+ 16. Qe5 Qxc6 17. Bf4 Bd7 $11 {
The position is completely equal.}) 8... Bd7 9. O-O Bd6 {We have reached an
important crossroads for the variation. White has a choice now. The most
natural follow-up seems to be} 10. b3 ({It's important to understand the
typical positions arising after} 10. Nf3 Bg4 {Black should pin the knight at
the first possible moment. As we are going to witness, in all the lines, White
does not manage to establish control of the d4-square.} 11. h3 {Forcing the
bishop to h5 is an important part of White's strategy, The reason will become
clear soon.} ({Another approach is} 11. Be2 O-O 12. b3 a6 {This is a generally
useful move in IQP positions. In this way, White does not have the manoeuvre
Nb5-d4 at his disposal.} ({In this particular position, it makes sense even to
take on f3 immediately, without any invitation -} 12... Bxf3 $5 13. Bxf3 Be5 14.
Bb2 Qa5 15. a3 d4 $1 {This typical break solves all the problems.} (15... Rac8
$2 16. b4 Qd8 17. Qb3 Qd6 18. h3 $16 {1/2 (42) Kholmov,R-Bronstein, D Moscow
1964}) 16. exd4 Nxd4 17. b4 Qa6 $11 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gf8e8] The position is equal.}
) 13. Bb2 Re8 14. Rc1 Bxf3 $6 {Black should have done this two moves earlier.
Now, White is prepared for the advance ...d5-d4.} ({Instead,} 14... Rc8 $5 {
would have been a better option. After} 15. h3 {Black should play the precise}
Bf5 $1 ({In response to} 15... Bh5 $6 {White can play} 16. Nd4 $1 {securing
the control of the d4-square after} Bxe2 17. Ncxe2 $14) 16. Bd3 Be4 $132 {
Black has decent compensation for his isolated pawn.}) ({Very similar is} 14...
Bc7 $5 15. h3 Bf5 16. Bd3 Be4 $132) 15. Bxf3 d4 $6 {Black is on the wrong
track.} ({Still, it was not too late for the standard} 15... Be5 $132) 16. exd4
Nxd4 $2 (16... Bf4 17. Rb1 Nxd4 18. Na4 $1 $14) 17. Bxb7 Ra7 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19.
Qxd4 Bxh2+ 20. Kxh2 Qxd4 21. Bxd4 Rxb7 22. Rfe1 $18 {1-0 (62) Radjabov,T (2765)
-Giri,A (2780) chess24.com INT 2021}) 11... Bh5 12. Be2 O-O 13. b3 a6 14. Bb2
Re8 15. Nh4 $5 {A very typical idea with reversed colours especially.} Bg6 $1 {
This is the thematic reaction. It's more important to exchange White's knight
in order to fight for d4-square.} ({The point behind White's idea can be seen
after} 15... Bxe2 $6 16. Nxe2 $14 {[%cal Gh4f5,Gh4f3] when White is slightly
better due to the increased control of the d4-square.}) 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Bf3
Be5 $11 {1/2 (110) Duda,J (2743)-Vidit,S (2726) chess24.com INT 2021}) ({
Forced attempt leads to massive exchanges and equality is} 10. e4 $5 {The next
few moves are pretty much forced.} Nxe4 11. Nxc6 (11. Nxd5 O-O $132) 11... Bxc6
12. Qxd5 O-O 13. Bxc6 Nxc3 {Only here, White has some choice. In any case,
however, Black has easy equality.} 14. Qf3 ({Winning a pawn by} 14. bxc3
bxc6 15. Qxc6 {leads to a forced draw after} Rc8 16. Qa6 (16. Qf3 Qc7 $11)
16... Rxc3 17. Qxa7 Qh4 18. g3 Bxg3 $1 $11 {with perpetual to follow.}) 14...
bxc6 15. Qxc3 Qc7 16. g3 Be5 17. Qc4 Rfd8 $1 {An important detail. Black wants
to secure the d4-square for his bishop.} (17... a5 18. Rb1 Rad8 19. Be3 Rfe8
20. Rfe1 $14 {1/2 (38) Cabarkapa,N (2453) -Vuckovic,B (2578) Ruma 2020}) 18.
Rb1 Bd4 $11) ({The move} 10. Be2 {looks like a loss of tempo but makes some
sense because the d7-bishop could be misplaced sometimes.} Nxd4 $5 {The most
principled choice. By sacrificing the d5-pawn, Black will make use of his
light-squared bishop.} (10... O-O 11. Ndb5 Bf5 12. Nxd6 Qxd6 13. Nb5 Qe5 {
could be also playable but at least White has some hopes due to the bishop pair
}) 11. Qxd4 O-O {[%cal Gd8c7,Gd6e5]} 12. Nxd5 {White should take the pawn.
Otherwise, Black would proceed with ...Qc7 followed by ...Be5.} (12. Rd1 Qc7
13. Qh4 Be5 $132) 12... Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Bc6 {[%csl Gg5,Gh4][%cal Gd8h4,Gd8g5]}
14. Qh5 g6 15. Qh3 Qb6 (15... Qf6 $5) 16. Bf3 Rac8 17. Bxc6 Rxc6 18. e4 Re8 $44
{Black had decent compensation for the pawn in the game 1/2 (31) Bricard, E  
(2465)-Gouret, T (2280) Dijon 1994}) 10... O-O 11. Bb2 Re8 12. Nce2 {The most
logical option in my opinion. White is trying to fortify the d4-square. The
alternatives are harmless.} ({After} 12. Rc1 {Black can play the natural} Rc8 (
{White should always keep in mind} 12... Nxd4 $5 13. Bxd7 Qxd7 14. Qxd4 Be5 $11
{with immediate equality.}) 13. Nxc6 $6 (13. Nce2 a6 14. Bd3 Nxd4 15. Nxd4
Rxc1 16. Qxc1 Ne4 $132) 13... bxc6 14. Be2 h5 $1 {[%cal Gf6g4,Gd8h4,Gd8g5] A
typical attacking idea for such structures. Black wants to proceed with ...Ng4
followed by ...Qg5 or ...Qh4. In such a case, Black's kingside attack would be
very dangerous.} 15. Qd4 Ng4 $40 {Black was already better in 1/2 (27)
Andreikin,D (2724)-Afanasiev,N (2540) Bryansk 2021}) ({As usual,} 12. Nf3 {
is well met by} Bg4 13. h3 ({The position arising after} 13. Bxc6 $6 bxc6 14.
Rc1 Be5 15. Na4 Bxb2 16. Nxb2 {offers Black adequate dynamic resources. Anand
played the normal} Rc8 ({Even more precise, however, might be} 16... Ne4 $1 $15
{when Black overtakes the initiative.}) 17. h3 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 c5 19. Rfd1 Qa5
20. Na4 c4 $11 {1/2 (60) So,W (2778)-Anand,V (2759) Leuven 2018}) 13... Bh5 14.
Be2 a6 15. Nh4 Bg6 $1 {we transpose to a position that was examined above.})
12... Be5 {It seems like Giri managed to equalize here after series of
exchanges.} ({But it also makes sense to put the knight on e4 and try to get a
kingside counterplay -} 12... a6 $5 13. Bd3 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 (14. Bxd4 Ng4 $132)
14... Ne4 $1 15. Nf3 (15. Rc1 Qh4) 15... Qe7 (15... Re6 $5) 16. Bc2 Bc6 $132 (
16... Qe6 $5 17. Qd4 Qg6 18. Qxd5 Bc6 19. Qa5 Rac8 {with rich compensation}))
13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bxe5 Rxe5 15. Bd3 c5 16. Rc1 Qb6 17. Qd2 Rc8 18. Rfd1 a5 19.
Nf4 a4 $11 {1/2 (40) Ding,L (2791)-Giri,A (2764) chess24.com INT 2020} *

